title: For Sale:  Stagarms 3G AR15 plus 22 CMMG upper, lots of extras + 60rd surefire
postcontent:
Bought this setup for 3-gun plus 22 plinking/training but I just don't use it like I thought I would

Rifle has 200 rounds through it from bench only, never used in competition (sort of why I'm selling it). Eats everything, meticulously cleaned and lubricated.

CMMG upper is NEW IN BOX I fit-checked it and never fired it, also includes 2 27-round BlackDog mags (pictured)

Vortex 1-4 scope is mounted and zeroed at 100 yards, beautiful optics! Pristine no scratches  or aberrations

Includes pictured mags and extras, 4 magpul 30-rnd, a Surefire 60rnd and the Magpul 20-rnd.

Notable extras are a Lula loader, some iron sights (a set of 45 degree offset sights) a Monstrum scope (combination green/red plus laser, intended to mount on the CMMG upper, but never did, it is NIB as well) and a Syrac Ordnance gas block (bought to tune a suppressor which I never got, this is also new and has never been mounted)

Case included.

I figure the street value breaks down something like this:
$1200 - rifle
$400 - Vortex 1x4 + mount
$400 - CMMG upper
$100 - mags
$200 - bipod + beater scope + extras

I hope you agree $1950 is a pretty good deal.

title: For Sale:  Colt Single Action Army Revolver
postcontent: This fine old pistol was shipped to Knoxville, TN on June 13, 1902.  The records I have show that it was owned by one William Coleman who was living in Knoxville at the time.  Further research shows that the only William Coleman listed as a resident of Knoxville at that time was a Civil War veteran "Wm Coleman, Co. A, 5th TN. Inf.  The records indicate that he passed away in 1917.  This Colt is a good honest gun that shows use but not abuse.  It is in 45 Colt caliber and has a 7 1/2 inch barrel.  This gun should make a fine addition to any Colt collection.

title: For Sale:  Colt Single Action Army
postcontent: This Colt is a pistol that has aged well and shows very little actual wear.  It was shipped from the Colt factory on April 30, 1895 and went to Houston, Texas.  The gun was purchased from the estate of Theodore L. Roberge who was a 35 year veteran of the U.S. Coast Guard where he served in WWII, Korea and Vietnam.  Dorothy Roberge, his widow said that the gun was originally purchased by his father or grandfather and had been in the family since new.  This fine old gun is about 60% in 45 Colt caliber. It sports a 5 1/2 inch barrel and has rubber grips.  This is an early "smokeless powder" model with a vertical screw holding the cylinder pin rather than the later horizontal latch system.  I firmly believe that this is one of the nicest "old" Colts I have seen and think it would make a fine addition to the most discriminating Colt collection.

• Soon to be available in your favorite color!

title: For Sale:  KEL-TEC KSG 12 Gauge 3"
postcontent:
YOU CAN BUY THIS HERE>KEL-TEC  KSG 12 Gauge 3"

The KSG (Kel-Tec Shotgun) is Kel-Tec CNC’s first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape, and design is similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1” overall length and an 18.5” cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3” rounds in total (6 per tube). It can also reliably shoot shells as short as 1 3/4" up to the 3".

This simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard.



The pump includes an under picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, a light, or a laser. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil.



The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward.

Technical Specificatons

Caliber:12 gauge 3”
Barrel length:18.5"
Total capacity:6+6+1
Weight empty:6.9lbs
Weight loaded:8.5lbs
Length:26.1"
Height:7"

title: For Sale:  Your Freedom!
postcontent:
The exceptions included in I-594 are drafted so narrowly that they are essentially meaningless.  

Examples:

There is NO general loan exemption for family members or friends, even in the presence of the owner!
You couldn’t loan your sister-in-law a firearm for self protection!
You couldn’t loan your adult sons shotguns to go hunting!
A person could “gift” a firearm to a family member but could NOT loan or sell it to her!
A police officer who loans a personal firearm to a fellow officer would face prosecution under I-594!
Concealed Pistol License holders, who are subjected to fingerprint-based checks, are not exempt!

Pass on this infographic which proves to any skeptic just how the law would work.

Full resolution version of the infographic here : 
http://www.plainsoftime.com/howtoexplainI594.png

NRA Analysis here:
https://www.voteno594.com/myths-vs-facts/

Local Police Analysis:
http://wslefia.com/?zone=/unionactive/view_page.cfm&page=I2D59420and20Law20Enforcement

title: For Sale/Trade:  Beretta 96 Brigadier Boarder Marshal Special !Still New In Box! 1 of 2000
postcontent:
This is the very rare and very collectable Model 96 Brigadier Boarder Marshal Special, it was only released it 2000 due to a contract with the government. They were made for the US Boarder Patrol and only 2000 were ever made of this model. Only a few other models had such a limited release. 

This handgun still sits new in its case and has never been fired, holstered, or taken to the range. It includes both factory 10 round (high capacity ban wasn't lifted until 2004) aluminum base magazines. The Brigadier heavy slide dovetailed with Trilux sights. Two sets of factory grips came with this model, the rubber and hard plastic. Shortened 4.7" chrome lined .40s&w barrel. Factory hard cases and original/Trilux manual. 

There is not wear the rails, hammer, feed ramp. No holster wear, no wear in the mag well, no barrel to slide contact wear that occurs as a round is fired in a 90 series... All because the handgun is truly new and unused. This is a collectors dream come true.

While this 96 Brigadier has never been fired I do own other 96 Brigadier pistols. And it is my honest opinion that the 96 Brigadier handles better than no other 40s&w pistol. The heavy weight Brigadier slide was specially designed for the .40s&w round.  

I collect Berettas and I'm in no rush to part with this piece, but would like to start acquiring firearms I can use and pass this on to another collector/Vets/Beretta enthusiast. Serious, educated offers only please, no low ballers, local exchanges only it at all possible. 

Price Not set yet, unable to find a like model to compare it to.
